Well, here’s a first: An AI agent is being sued for being too good at its job. 

Okay, technically it is the team responsible for designing and using that AI agent that is being sued. 

Also, the team is called Microsoft. Ever heard of it? 

Well, Microsoft’s AI agent goes by the name of CoPilot, and it has gotten them into a little bit of trouble. 

Specifically, a lawsuit from Matthew Butterick, Los Angeles lawyer and writer who sees some serious issues with how AI agents do the work they’ve been trained to do. 

What issues could that be? 

Well, consider what CoPilot does. 

It is a generative AI agent that creates code that is recommended to programmers working on lines of code. 

The purpose, of course, is to assist programmers in writing better code. It is like having a creative partner who is incredibly knowledgeable about how to write lines of code. 

How that knowledge was gained is where the troubles begin. 

Troubles with the Training Phase?

AI is trained to do a task, such as writing code, by being shown examples of a job-well-done, such as code that was written by human programmers, who may not be getting the credit for their work that informs the AI agent. 

The lawsuit claim then is that the AI agent is basically a form of piracy, as the training-phase work goes uncredited. 

What the Outcome Might Mean for the Future of AI

This is a decision within the courts of law that will have ramifications for the future development and application of artificial intelligence platforms. 

Depending on whether this is considered a form of plagiarism, AI developers will be much more limited in how they train AI.

The secret sauce? Humanization.

In the B2B world, you’re not just talking to logos and brands; you’re talking to actual people. 

People who, by the way, are making decisions about your product while scrolling through their feeds in pajamas.

So, humanize your brand. Show the faces behind the operations. It’s like revealing the wizard behind the curtain in Oz, but less intimidating and more relatable.

Whether you’re in the B2C or B2B game, the bottom line is you’re dealing with people. 

And people, whether they’re buying a gadget or a gigantic corporate solution, all want to feel like they’re doing business with someone who gets them.
